This is a python3  directory. It holds code for the Gui_async_client.

The code here may be run in a host terminal with virtual environment, python3.
Gui_async_client's purpose is to respond to User inputs to generate messages with commands to the Server and the Adc_async_client,
Gui_async_client will  display information from both to the User. 
User will see info on the status of a 3-pack of 18650 Lithium Ion battery cells.
Voltage taps on the cells provides three channels: One cell, Two cells, Three cells.
The server and/or the Gui_async_client can compute the voltages for each of the three by subtraction of the voltage measurements.
The Gui_async_client commands are listed in the table below.
There may be many hosts that perform the Gui_async_client functions: mobile, desktop, laptop, etc.
The Server receives the commands via asyncio from the Gui_asyncio_client and forwards them to Adc_async_client.
Upon receiving the report back from the Server, the  Gui_async_client displays the information  to the user.  
Then it sends via asyncio_connection a message to the Server in which is embedded the cmd attributes.
A measurment command (100) will result in 3 measurement reports, each with voltage measurements for ( One cell , Two Cells, Three Cells)
A calibration command(200) will be for a single channel and will contain the Truth value, called "vin" for input voltage . 
A calibration command will result in one calibration_report(201) msg sent to the Server with "vin" embedded along with normal samples and neccesary fields.
For the Start_Periodic cmd,  Gui_async_client will pass two attributes thru the Server to the Adc_async_client, Start_Periodic.period and Start_Periodic.repetitions.
A measurement(100) and a calibration(200) command will vary in three ways: the type ('m','c') and vin = [0, truthValue], where 'm' means measure and 'c' means calibrate and calibration is chan specific.
The time between cmd and response is estimated to be ~5 seconds.
A small amount of time will be expended in translating incoming msgs and formatting outgoing messages.
The Gui_async_client will allow the User to update database tables as needed.
Reports from the Server on database tables will include the id to facilitate updates.
Many apps can be run on this system, the app_id will allow the tables to respond to app_id and version.
The Configuration of the App will be versioned. 
The Gui_async_client will set app_id, and version so that tables are in sync with the current configuration.

Summary:
1. Code must run in python3 to allow for larger frameworks in virtual environments.
2. Client must be able to issue cmds and receive reports via json and asyncio
3. User must embed "CODE" and "ARGSLIST", [...], for some dbi calls. 
4. Future work could allow Gui_async_client to specify changes in the number of samples, sample_rate, etc, but is frozen for now.
5. Process latency estimated to be less than 5 seconds.
6. Msg sizes must be less than 1kb.




Commands that the Gui_async_client can send. These may change as needed. They may be simplified.

cmd[100]= 'request_measure'                 #all chans ; will result in (3)reports 101s
cmd[101]= 'response_measurement'
cmd[150]= 'request past_records'            # (chan,type)
cmd[175]= 'set_up_periodic_measurements'
cmd[300]= 'save_config'
cmd[310]= 'request_config chan'            # (chan)
cmd[311]= 'response_config'                # (chan)
cmd[350]= 'update_lut'                     # (id, version , chan, vm, vin)  embedded in json
cmd[360]= 'request_lut'                    # (chan)
cmd[361]= 'responselut'                    # (chan)
cmd[370]= 'request_lut_timestamp'          # (chan)
cmd[371]= 'response_lut_timestamp'         # (chan)


